[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Grammatical error detection and correction involves a great bandwidth of problems on all levels of linguistic analysis (phonology/orthography, morphology, syntax, semantics, pragmatics).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Grammatical error correction is impactful since it affects hundreds of millions of people who use or acquire English as a second language.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] It has thus been subject to a number of shared tasks since 2011.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] , this can now (2019) be considered a largely solved problem and is being marketed in various commercial applications.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Translate a text from a natural language into formal logic.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Automatically translate text from one human language to another.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] ", i.e. requiring all of the different types of knowledge that humans possess (grammar, semantics, facts about the real world, etc.) to solve properly.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Natural language understanding involves the identification of the intended semantic from the multiple possible semantics that can be derived from a natural language expression which usually takes the form of organized notations of natural language concepts.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Introduction and creation of language metamodels and ontologies are efficient but empirical solutions.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] , or subjective Yes/No vs. objective True/False is expected for the construction of a basis of semantics formalization.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Convert information from computer databases or semantic intents into readable human language.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Not an NLP task proper but an extension of natural language generation and other NLP tasks is the creation of full-fledged books.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] , marketed as a novel, contains sixty million words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] , this is grounded on factual knowledge and based on text summarization.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] A Document AI platform sits on top of the NLP technology enabling users with no prior experience of artificial intelligence, machine learning or NLP to quickly train a computer to extract the specific data they need from different document types.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] NLP-powered Document AI enables non-technical teams to quickly access information hidden in documents, for example, lawyers, business analysts and accountants.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Computer systems intended to converse with a human.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Given a human-language question, determine its answer.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Typical questions have a specific right answer (such as "What is the capital of Canada?"), but sometimes open-ended questions are also considered (such as "What is the meaning of life?").
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Given a description of an image, generate an image that matches the description.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Given a description of a video, generate a video that matches the description.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Based on long-standing trends in the field, it is possible to extrapolate future directions of NLP.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Most higher-level NLP applications involve aspects that emulate intelligent behavior and apparent comprehension of natural language.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] More broadly speaking, the technical operationalization of increasingly advanced aspects of cognitive behavior represents one of the developmental trajectories of NLP(see trends among CoNLL shared tasks above).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Cognition refers to "the mental action or process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses." Cognitive science is the interdisciplinary, scientific study of the mind and its processes.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Cognitive linguistics is an interdisciplinary branch of linguistics, combining knowledge and research from both psychology and linguistics.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Especially during the age of symbolic NLP, the area of computational linguistics maintained strong ties with cognitive studies.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Assign relative measures of meaning to a word, phrase, sentence or piece of text based on the information presented before and after the piece of text being analyzed, e.g., by means of a probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] Ties with cognitive linguistics are part of the historical heritage of NLP, but they have been less frequently addressed since the statistical turn during the 1990s.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/natural-language-processing] More recently, ideas of cognitive NLP have been revived as an approach to achieve explainability, e.g., under the notion of "cognitive AI".
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] In natural language processing, a **word embedding** is a representation of a word.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes the meaning of the word in such a way that the words that are closer in the vector space are expected to be similar in meaning.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Word embeddings can be obtained using language modeling and feature learning techniques, where words or phrases from the vocabulary are mapped to vectors of real numbers.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Methods to generate this mapping include neural networks, dimensionality reduction on the word co-occurrence matrix, probabilistic models, explainable knowledge base method, and explicit representation in terms of the context in which words appear.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Word and phrase embeddings, when used as the underlying input representation, have been shown to boost the performance in NLP tasks such as syntactic parsing and sentiment analysis.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] In distributional semantics, a quantitative methodological approach for understanding meaning in observed language, word embeddings or semantic feature space models have been used as a knowledge representation for some time.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Such models aim to quantify and categorize semantic similarities between linguistic items based on their distributional properties in large samples of language data.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The underlying idea that "a word is characterized by the company it keeps" was proposed in a 1957 article by John Rupert Firth, but also has roots in the contemporaneous work on search systems and in cognitive psychology.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The first generation of semantic space models is the vector space model for information retrieval.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Such vector space models for words and their distributional data implemented in their simplest form results in a very sparse vector space of high dimensionality (cf. curse of dimensionality).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Reducing the number of dimensions using linear algebraic methods such as singular value decomposition then led to the introduction of latent semantic analysis in the late 1980s and the random indexing approach for collecting word co-occurrence contexts.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] In 2000, Bengio et al. provided in a series of papers titled "Neural probabilistic language models" to reduce the high dimensionality of word representations in contexts by "learning a distributed representation for words".
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] A study published in NeurIPS (NIPS) 2002 introduced the use of both word and document embeddings applying the method of kernel CCA to bilingual (and multi-lingual) corpora, also providing an early example of self-supervised learning of word embeddings.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Word embeddings come in two different styles, one in which words are expressed as vectors of co-occurring words, and another in which words are expressed as vectors of linguistic contexts in which the words occur; these different styles are studied in Lavelli et al., 2004.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Roweis and Saul published in *Science* how to use "locally linear embedding" (LLE) to discover representations of high dimensional data structures.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Most new word embedding techniques after about 2005 rely on a neural network architecture instead of more probabilistic and algebraic models, after foundational work done by Yoshua Bengio and colleagues.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The approach has been adopted by many research groups after theoretical advances in 2010 had been made on the quality of vectors and the training speed of the model, as well as after hardware advances allowed for a broader parameter space to be explored profitably.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] In 2013, a team at Google led by Tomas Mikolov created word2vec, a word embedding toolkit that can train vector space models faster than previous approaches.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The word2vec approach has been widely used in experimentation and was instrumental in raising interest for word embeddings as a technology, moving the research strand out of specialised research into broader experimentation and eventually paving the way for practical application.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Historically, one of the main limitations of static word embeddings or word vector space models is that words with multiple meanings are conflated into a single representation (a single vector in the semantic space).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] In other words, polysemy and homonymy are not handled properly.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] For example, in the sentence "The club I tried yesterday was great!", it is not clear if the term *club* is related to the word sense of a *club sandwich*, *clubhouse*, *golf club*, or any other sense that *club* might have.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The necessity to accommodate multiple meanings per word in different vectors (multi-sense embeddings) is the motivation for several contributions in NLP to split single-sense embeddings into multi-sense ones.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Most approaches that produce multi-sense embeddings can be divided into two main categories for their word sense representation, i.e., unsupervised and knowledge-based.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Based on word2vec skip-gram, Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (MSSG) performs word-sense discrimination and embedding simultaneously, improving its training time, while assuming a specific number of senses for each word.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] In the Non-Parametric Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (NP-MSSG) this number can vary depending on each word.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Once the words are disambiguated, they can be used in a standard word embeddings technique, so multi-sense embeddings are produced.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] MSSA architecture allows the disambiguation and annotation process to be performed recurrently in a self-improving manner.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The use of multi-sense embeddings is known to improve performance in several NLP tasks, such as part-of-speech tagging, semantic relation identification, semantic relatedness, named entity recognition and sentiment analysis.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] As of the late 2010s, contextually-meaningful embeddings such as ELMo and BERT have been developed.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Unlike static word embeddings, these embeddings are at the token-level, in that each occurrence of a word has its own embedding.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] These embeddings better reflect the multi-sense nature of words, because occurrences of a word in similar contexts are situated in similar regions of BERT's embedding space.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Word embeddings for *n-*grams in biological sequences (e.g.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] DNA, RNA, and proteins) for bioinformatics applications have been proposed by Asgari and Mofrad.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Named bio-vectors (BioVec) to refer to biological sequences in general with protein-vectors (ProtVec) for proteins (amino-acid sequences) and gene-vectors (GeneVec) for gene sequences, this representation can be widely used in applications of deep learning in proteomics and genomics.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The results presented by Asgari and Mofrad suggest that BioVectors can characterize biological sequences in terms of biochemical and biophysical interpretations of the underlying patterns.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Word embeddings with applications in game design have been proposed by Rabii and Cook as a way to discover emergent gameplay using logs of gameplay data.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The process requires transcribing actions that occur during a game within a formal language and then using the resulting text to create word embeddings.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The results presented by Rabii and Cook suggest that the resulting vectors can capture expert knowledge about games like chess that are not explicitly stated in the game's rules.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] The idea has been extended to embeddings of entire sentences or even documents, e.g. in the form of the thought vectors concept.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] In 2015, some researchers suggested "skip-thought vectors" as a means to improve the quality of machine translation.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] A more recent and popular approach for representing sentences is Sentence-BERT, or SentenceTransformers, which modifies pre-trained BERT with the use of siamese and triplet network structures.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Software for training and using word embeddings includes Tomáš Mikolov's Word2vec, Stanford University's GloVe, GN-GloVe, Flair embeddings, AllenNLP's ELMo, BERT, fastText, Gensim, Indra, and Deeplearning4j.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Principal Component Analysis (PCA), Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP), and T-Distributed Stochastic Neighbour Embedding (t-SNE) are used to reduce the dimensionality of word vector spaces and visualize word embeddings and clusters.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] For instance, the fastText is also used to calculate word embeddings for text corpora in Sketch Engine that are available online.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Word embeddings may contain the biases and stereotypes contained in the trained dataset, as Bolukbasi et al. points out in the 2016 paper "Man is to Computer Programmer as Woman is to Homemaker?
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] For example, one of the analogies generated using the aforementioned word embedding is "man is to computer programmer as woman is to homemaker".
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Research done by Jieyu Zhao et al. shows that the applications of these trained word embeddings without careful oversight likely perpetuates existing bias in society, which is introduced through unaltered training data.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-embedding] Furthermore, word embeddings can even amplify these biases.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Given that natural language requires reflection of neurological reality, as shaped by the abilities provided by the brain's neural networks, computer science has had a long-term challenge in developing the ability in computers to do natural language processing and machine learning.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Among these, supervised learning approaches have been the most successful algorithms to date.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The accuracy of current algorithms is difficult to state without a host of caveats.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In English, accuracy at the coarse-grained (homograph) level is routinely above 90% (as of 2009), with some methods on particular homographs achieving over 96%.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] On finer-grained sense distinctions, top accuracies from 59.1% to 69.0% have been reported in evaluation exercises (SemEval-2007, Senseval-2), where the baseline accuracy of the simplest possible algorithm of always choosing the most frequent sense was 51.4% and 57%, respectively.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Disambiguation requires two strict inputs: a dictionary to specify the senses which are to be disambiguated and a corpus of language data to be disambiguated (in some methods, a training corpus of language examples is also required).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] WSD task has two variants: "lexical sample" (disambiguating the occurrences of a small sample of target words which were previously selected) and "all words" task (disambiguation of all the words in a running text).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] WSD was first formulated as a distinct computational task during the early days of machine translation in the 1940s, making it one of the oldest problems in computational linguistics.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Warren Weaver first introduced the problem in a computational context in his 1949 memorandum on translation.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Later, Bar-Hillel (1960) argued that WSD could not be solved by "electronic computer" because of the need in general to model all world knowledge.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In the 1970s, WSD was a subtask of semantic interpretation systems developed within the field of artificial intelligence, starting with Wilks' preference semantics.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] However, since WSD systems were at the time largely rule-based and hand-coded they were prone to a knowledge acquisition bottleneck.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] By the 1980s large-scale lexical resources, such as the Oxford Advanced Learner's Dictionary of Current English (OALD), became available: hand-coding was replaced with knowledge automatically extracted from these resources, but disambiguation was still knowledge-based or dictionary-based.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In the 1990s, the statistical revolution advanced computational linguistics, and WSD became a paradigm problem on which to apply supervised machine learning techniques.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The 2000s saw supervised techniques reach a plateau in accuracy, and so attention has shifted to coarser-grained senses, domain adaptation, semi-supervised and unsupervised corpus-based systems, combinations of different methods, and the return of knowledge-based systems via graph-based methods.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Still, supervised systems continue to perform best.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] One problem with word sense disambiguation is deciding what the senses are, as different dictionaries and thesauruses will provide different divisions of words into senses.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Some researchers have suggested choosing a particular dictionary, and using its set of senses to deal with this issue.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Generally, however, research results using broad distinctions in senses have been much better than those using narrow ones.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Most researchers continue to work on fine-grained WSD.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Most research in the field of WSD is performed by using WordNet as a reference sense inventory for English.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] WordNet is a computational lexicon that encodes concepts as synonym sets (e.g. the concept of car is encoded as { car, auto, automobile, machine, motorcar }).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Other resources used for disambiguation purposes include Roget's Thesaurus and Wikipedia.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] More recently, BabelNet, a multilingual encyclopedic dictionary, has been used for multilingual WSD.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In any real test, part-of-speech tagging and sense tagging have proven to be very closely related, with each potentially imposing constraints upon the other.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The question of whether these tasks should be kept together or decoupled is still not unanimously resolved, but recently scientists incline to test these things separately (e.g. in the Senseval/SemEval competitions parts of speech are provided as input for the text to disambiguate).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Both WSD and part-of-speech tagging involve disambiguating or tagging with words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] However, algorithms used for one do not tend to work well for the other, mainly because the part of speech of a word is primarily determined by the immediately adjacent one to three words, whereas the sense of a word may be determined by words further away.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The success rate for part-of-speech tagging algorithms is at present much higher than that for WSD, state-of-the art being around 96% accuracy or better, as compared to less than 75% accuracy in word sense disambiguation with supervised learning.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] These figures are typical for English, and may be very different from those for other languages.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Another problem is inter-judge variance.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] WSD systems are normally tested by having their results on a task compared against those of a human.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] However, while it is relatively easy to assign parts of speech to text, training people to tag senses has been proven to be far more difficult.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] While users can memorize all of the possible parts of speech a word can take, it is often impossible for individuals to memorize all of the senses a word can take.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Moreover, humans do not agree on the task at hand – give a list of senses and sentences, and humans will not always agree on which word belongs in which sense.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] As human performance serves as the standard, it is an upper bound for computer performance.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Human performance, however, is much better on coarse-grained than fine-grained distinctions, so this again is why research on coarse-grained distinctions has been put to test in recent WSD evaluation exercises.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] A task-independent sense inventory is not a coherent concept: each task requires its own division of word meaning into senses relevant to the task.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Additionally, completely different algorithms might be required by different applications.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In machine translation, the problem takes the form of target word selection.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The "senses" are words in the target language, which often correspond to significant meaning distinctions in the source language ("bank" could translate to the French *banque* – that is, 'financial bank' or *rive* – that is, 'edge of river').
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In information retrieval, a sense inventory is not necessarily required, because it is enough to know that a word is used in the same sense in the query and a retrieved document; what sense that is, is unimportant.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Finally, the very notion of "word sense" is slippery and controversial.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Most people can agree in distinctions at the coarse-grained homograph level (e.g., pen as writing instrument or enclosure), but go down one level to fine-grained polysemy, and disagreements arise.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] For example, in Senseval-2, which used fine-grained sense distinctions, human annotators agreed in only 85% of word occurrences.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Word meaning is in principle infinitely variable and context-sensitive.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] It does not divide up easily into distinct or discrete sub-meanings.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Lexicographers frequently discover in corpora loose and overlapping word meanings, and standard or conventional meanings extended, modulated, and exploited in a bewildering variety of ways.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The art of lexicography is to generalize from the corpus to definitions that evoke and explain the full range of meaning of a word, making it seem like words are well-behaved semantically.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] However, it is not at all clear if these same meaning distinctions are applicable in computational applications, as the decisions of lexicographers are usually driven by other considerations.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In 2009, a task – named lexical substitution – was proposed as a possible solution to the sense discreteness problem.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The task consists of providing a substitute for a word in context that preserves the meaning of the original word (potentially, substitutes can be chosen from the full lexicon of the target language, thus overcoming discreteness).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] There are two main approaches to WSD – deep approaches and shallow approaches.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Deep approaches presume access to a comprehensive body of world knowledge.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] These approaches are generally not considered to be very successful in practice, mainly because such a body of knowledge does not exist in a computer-readable format, outside very limited domains.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Additionally due to the long tradition in computational linguistics of trying such approaches in terms of coded knowledge and in some cases, it can be hard to distinguish between knowledge involved in linguistic or world knowledge.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The first attempt was that by Margaret Masterman and her colleagues, at the Cambridge Language Research Unit in England, in the 1950s.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] This attempt used as data a punched-card version of Roget's Thesaurus and its numbered "heads", as an indicator of topics and looked for repetitions in text, using a set intersection algorithm.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] It was not very successful, but had strong relationships to later work, especially Yarowsky's machine learning optimisation of a thesaurus method in the 1990s.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Shallow approaches do not try to understand the text, but instead consider the surrounding words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] These rules can be automatically derived by the computer, using a training corpus of words tagged with their word senses.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] This approach, while theoretically not as powerful as deep approaches, gives superior results in practice, due to the computer's limited world knowledge.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Almost all these approaches work by defining a window of *n* content words around each word to be disambiguated in the corpus, and statistically analyzing those *n* surrounding words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Two shallow approaches used to train and then disambiguate are Naïve Bayes classifiers and decision trees.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In recent research, kernel-based methods such as support vector machines have shown superior performance in supervised learning.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Graph-based approaches have also gained much attention from the research community, and currently achieve performance close to the state of the art.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The Lesk algorithm is the seminal dictionary-based method.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] It is based on the hypothesis that words used together in text are related to each other and that the relation can be observed in the definitions of the words and their senses.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Two (or more) words are disambiguated by finding the pair of dictionary senses with the greatest word overlap in their dictionary definitions.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] For example, when disambiguating the words in "pine cone", the definitions of the appropriate senses both include the words evergreen and tree (at least in one dictionary).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] A similar approach searches for the shortest path between two words: the second word is iteratively searched among the definitions of every semantic variant of the first word, then among the definitions of every semantic variant of each word in the previous definitions and so on.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Finally, the first word is disambiguated by selecting the semantic variant which minimizes the distance from the first to the second word.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] An alternative to the use of the definitions is to consider general word-sense relatedness and to compute the semantic similarity of each pair of word senses based on a given lexical knowledge base such as WordNet.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Graph-based methods reminiscent of spreading activation research of the early days of AI research have been applied with some success.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] More complex graph-based approaches have been shown to perform almost as well as supervised methods or even outperform them on specific domains.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Recently, it has been reported that simple graph connectivity measures, such as degree, perform state-of-the-art WSD in the presence of a sufficiently rich lexical knowledge base.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Also, automatically transferring knowledge in the form of semantic relations from Wikipedia to WordNet has been shown to boost simple knowledge-based methods, enabling them to rival the best supervised systems and even outperform them in a domain-specific setting.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The use of selectional preferences (or selectional restrictions) is also useful; for example, knowing that one typically cooks food, one can disambiguate the word bass in "I am cooking basses" (i.e., it's not a musical instrument).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Supervised methods are based on the assumption that the context can provide enough evidence on its own to disambiguate words (hence, common sense and reasoning are deemed unnecessary).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Probably every machine learning algorithm going has been applied to WSD, including associated techniques such as feature selection, parameter optimization, and ensemble learning.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Support Vector Machines and memory-based learning have been shown to be the most successful approaches to date, probably because they can cope with the high-dimensionality of the feature space.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] However, these supervised methods are subject to a new knowledge acquisition bottleneck since they rely on substantial amounts of manually sense-tagged corpora for training, which are laborious and expensive to create.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Because of the lack of training data, many word sense disambiguation algorithms use semi-supervised learning, which allows both labeled and unlabeled data.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The Yarowsky algorithm was an early example of such an algorithm.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] It uses the ‘One sense per collocation’ and the ‘One sense per discourse’ properties of human languages for word sense disambiguation.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] From observation, words tend to exhibit only one sense in most given discourse and in a given collocation.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The bootstrapping approach starts from a small amount of seed data for each word: either manually tagged training examples or a small number of surefire decision rules (e.g., 'play' in the context of 'bass' almost always indicates the musical instrument).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The seeds are used to train an initial classifier, using any supervised method.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] This classifier is then used on the untagged portion of the corpus to extract a larger training set, in which only the most confident classifications are included.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The process repeats, each new classifier being trained on a successively larger training corpus, until the whole corpus is consumed, or until a given maximum number of iterations is reached.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Other semi-supervised techniques use large quantities of untagged corpora to provide co-occurrence information that supplements the tagged corpora.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] These techniques have the potential to help in the adaptation of supervised models to different domains.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Also, an ambiguous word in one language is often translated into different words in a second language depending on the sense of the word.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Word-aligned bilingual corpora have been used to infer cross-lingual sense distinctions, a kind of semi-supervised system.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Unsupervised learning is the greatest challenge for WSD researchers.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The underlying assumption is that similar senses occur in similar contexts, and thus senses can be induced from text by clustering word occurrences using some measure of similarity of context, a task referred to as word sense induction or discrimination.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Then, new occurrences of the word can be classified into the closest induced clusters/senses.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Performance has been lower than for the other methods described above, but comparisons are difficult since senses induced must be mapped to a known dictionary of word senses.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] If a mapping to a set of dictionary senses is not desired, cluster-based evaluations (including measures of entropy and purity) can be performed.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Alternatively, word sense induction methods can be tested and compared within an application.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] For instance, it has been shown that word sense induction improves Web search result clustering by increasing the quality of result clusters and the degree of diversification of result lists.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] It is hoped that unsupervised learning will overcome the knowledge acquisition bottleneck because they are not dependent on manual effort.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Representing words considering their context through fixed-size dense vectors (word embeddings) has become one of the most fundamental blocks in several NLP systems.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Even though most of traditional word-embedding techniques conflate words with multiple meanings into a single vector representation, they still can be used to improve WSD.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] A simple approach to employ pre-computed word embeddings to represent word senses is to compute the centroids of sense clusters.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In addition to word-embedding techniques, lexical databases (e.g., WordNet, ConceptNet, BabelNet) can also assist unsupervised systems in mapping words and their senses as dictionaries.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Some techniques that combine lexical databases and word embeddings are presented in AutoExtend and Most Suitable Sense Annotation (MSSA).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In AutoExtend, they present a method that decouples an object input representation into its properties, such as words and their word senses.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] AutoExtend uses a graph structure to map words (e.g. text) and non-word (e.g. synsets in WordNet) objects as nodes and the relationship between nodes as edges.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The relations (edges) in AutoExtend can either express the addition or similarity between its nodes.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The former captures the intuition behind the offset calculus, while the latter defines the similarity between two nodes.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In MSSA, an unsupervised disambiguation system uses the similarity between word senses in a fixed context window to select the most suitable word sense using a pre-trained word-embedding model and WordNet.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] For each context window, MSSA calculates the centroid of each word sense definition by averaging the word vectors of its words in WordNet's glosses (i.e., short defining gloss and one or more usage examples) using a pre-trained word-embedding model.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] These centroids are later used to select the word sense with the highest similarity of a target word to its immediately adjacent neighbors (i.e., predecessor and successor words).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] After all words are annotated and disambiguated, they can be used as a training corpus in any standard word-embedding technique.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In its improved version, MSSA can make use of word sense embeddings to repeat its disambiguation process iteratively.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The knowledge acquisition bottleneck is perhaps the major impediment to solving the WSD problem.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Unsupervised methods rely on knowledge about word senses, which is only sparsely formulated in dictionaries and lexical databases.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Supervised methods depend crucially on the existence of manually annotated examples for every word sense, a requisite that can so far be met only for a handful of words for testing purposes, as it is done in the Senseval exercises.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] One of the most promising trends in WSD research is using the largest corpus ever accessible, the World Wide Web, to acquire lexical information automatically.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] WSD has been traditionally understood as an intermediate language engineering technology which could improve applications such as information retrieval (IR).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In this case, however, the reverse is also true: web search engines implement simple and robust IR techniques that can successfully mine the Web for information to use in WSD.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The historic lack of training data has provoked the appearance of some new algorithms and techniques, as described in Automatic acquisition of sense-tagged corpora.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Knowledge is a fundamental component of WSD.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Knowledge sources provide data which are essential to associate senses with words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] They can vary from corpora of texts, either unlabeled or annotated with word senses, to machine-readable dictionaries, thesauri, glossaries, ontologies, etc.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Comparing and evaluating different WSD systems is extremely difficult, because of the different test sets, sense inventories, and knowledge resources adopted.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Before the organization of specific evaluation campaigns most systems were assessed on in-house, often small-scale, data sets.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In order to test one's algorithm, developers should spend their time annotating all word occurrences.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] And comparing methods even on the same corpus is not possible if there is different sense inventories.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In order to define common evaluation datasets and procedures, public evaluation campaigns have been organized.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] Senseval (now renamed SemEval) is an international word sense disambiguation competition, held every three years since 1998: Senseval-1 Archived 2011-07-17 at the Wayback Machine (1998), Senseval-2 (2001), Senseval-3 (2004), and its successor, SemEval (2007).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] The systems submitted for evaluation to these competitions usually integrate different techniques and often combine supervised and knowledge-based methods (especially for avoiding bad performance due to a lack of training examples).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/word-sense-disambiguation] In recent years 2007-2012, the WSD evaluation task choices have grown and the criterion for evaluating WSD has changed drastically depending on the variant of the WSD evaluation task.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet was first created in 1985, in English only, in the Cognitive Science Laboratory of Princeton University under the direction of psychology professor George Armitage Miller.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] It was later directed by Christiane Fellbaum.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The project was initially funded by the U.S.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Office of Naval Research, and later also by other U.S. government agencies including the DARPA, the National Science Foundation, the Disruptive Technology Office (formerly the Advanced Research and Development Activity) and REFLEX.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] George Miller and Christiane Fellbaum received the 2006 Antonio Zampolli Prize for their work with WordNet.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The Global WordNet Association is a non-commercial organization that provides a platform for discussing, sharing and connecting WordNets for all languages in the world.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The database contains 155,327 words organized in 175,979 synsets for a total of 207,016 word-sense pairs; in compressed form, it is about 12 megabytes in size.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] It includes the lexical categories nouns, verbs, adjectives and adverbs but ignores prepositions, determiners and other function words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Words from the same lexical category that are roughly synonymous are grouped into synsets, which include simplex words as well as collocations like "eat out" and "car pool." The different senses of a polysemous word form are assigned to different synsets.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] A synset's meaning is further clarified with a short defining *gloss* and one or more usage examples.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] All synsets are connected by means of semantic relations.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] These semantic relations hold among all members of the linked synsets.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Individual synset members (words) can also be connected with lexical relations.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] For example, (one sense of) the noun "director" is linked to (one sense of) the verb "direct" from which it is derived via a "morphosemantic" link.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The morphology functions of the software distributed with the database try to deduce the lemma or stem form of a word from the user's input.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Irregular forms are stored in a list, and looking up "ate" will return "eat," for example.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Both nouns and verbs are organized into hierarchies, defined by hypernym or *IS A* relationships.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] For instance, one sense of the word *dog* is found following hypernym hierarchy; the words at the same level represent synset members.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Each set of synonyms has a unique index.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] At the top level, these hierarchies are organized into 25 beginner "trees" for nouns and 15 for verbs (called *lexicographic files* at a maintenance level).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] All are linked to a unique beginner synset, "entity".
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Noun hierarchies are far deeper than verb hierarchies.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Adjectives are not organized into hierarchical trees.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Instead, two "central" antonyms such as "hot" and "cold" form binary poles, while 'satellite' synonyms such as "steaming" and "chilly" connect to their respective poles via a "similarity" relations.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The adjectives can be visualized in this way as "dumbbells" rather than as "trees".
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The initial goal of the WordNet project was to build a lexical database that would be consistent with theories of human semantic memory developed in the late 1960s.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Psychological experiments indicated that speakers organized their knowledge of concepts in an economic, hierarchical fashion.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Retrieval time required to access conceptual knowledge seemed to be directly related to the number of hierarchies the speaker needed to "traverse" to access the knowledge.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] While such psycholinguistic experiments and the underlying theories have been subject to criticism, some of WordNet's organization is consistent with experimental evidence.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] For example, anomic aphasia selectively affects speakers' ability to produce words from a specific semantic category, a WordNet hierarchy.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Antonymous adjectives (WordNet's central adjectives in the dumbbell structure) are found to co-occur far more frequently than chance, a fact that has been found to hold for many languages.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet is sometimes called an ontology, a persistent claim that its creators do not make.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The hypernym/hyponym relationships among the noun synsets can be interpreted as specialization relations among conceptual categories.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] In other words, WordNet can be interpreted and used as a lexical ontology in the computer science sense.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] However, such an ontology should be corrected before being used, because it contains hundreds of basic semantic inconsistencies; for example there are, (i) common specializations for exclusive categories and (ii) redundancies in the specialization hierarchy.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Furthermore, transforming WordNet into a lexical ontology usable for knowledge representation should normally also involve (i) distinguishing the specialization relations into *subtypeOf* and *instanceOf* relations, and (ii) associating intuitive unique identifiers to each category.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet has also been converted to a formal specification, by means of a hybrid bottom-up top-down methodology to automatically extract association relations from it and interpret these associations in terms of a set of conceptual relations, formally defined in the DOLCE foundational ontology.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] In most works that claim to have integrated WordNet into ontologies, the content of WordNet has not simply been corrected when it seemed necessary; instead, it has been heavily reinterpreted and updated whenever suitable.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] This was the case when, for example, the top-level ontology of WordNet was restructured according to the OntoClean-based approach, or when it was used as a primary source for constructing the lower classes of the SENSUS ontology.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The most widely discussed limitation of WordNet (and related resources like ImageNet) is that some of the semantic relations are more suited to concrete concepts than to abstract concepts.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Many of the concepts in WordNet are specific to certain languages and the most accurate reported mapping between languages is 94%.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Synonyms, hyponyms, meronyms, and antonyms occur in all languages with a WordNet so far, but other semantic relationships are language-specific.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] This limits the interoperability across languages.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] However, it also makes WordNet a resource for highlighting and studying the differences between languages, so it is not necessarily a limitation for all use cases.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet does not include information about the etymology or the pronunciation of words and it contains only limited information about usage.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet aims to cover most everyday words and does not include much domain-specific terminology.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet is the most commonly used computational lexicon of English for word-sense disambiguation (WSD), a task aimed at assigning the context-appropriate meanings (i.e. synset members) to words in a text.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] However, it has been argued that WordNet encodes sense distinctions that are too fine-grained.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] This issue prevents WSD systems from achieving a level of performance comparable to that of humans, who do not always agree when confronted with the task of selecting a sense from a dictionary that matches a word in a context.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The granularity issue has been tackled by proposing clustering methods that automatically group together similar senses of the same word.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet includes words that can be perceived as pejorative or offensive.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The interpretation of a word can change over time and between social groups, so it is not always possible for WordNet to define a word as "pejorative" or "offensive" in isolation.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Therefore, people using WordNet must apply their own methods to identify offensive or pejorative words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] However, this limitation is true of other lexical resources like dictionaries and thesauruses, which also contain pejorative and offensive words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Some dictionaries indicate words that are pejoratives, but do not include all the contexts in which words might be acceptable or offensive to different social groups.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Therefore, people using dictionaries must apply their own methods to identify all offensive words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Some wordnets were subsequently created for other languages.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] A 2012 survey lists the wordnets and their availability.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The Open Multilingual Wordnet provides access to open licensed wordnets in a variety of languages.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Version 1 is linked to the Princeton Wordnet of English, while version 2 uses an independent index (the Collaborative Interlingual Index).
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The goal is to make it easy to use wordnets in multiple languages.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet has been used for a number of purposes in information systems, including word-sense disambiguation, information retrieval, automatic text classification, automatic text summarization, machine translation and even automatic crossword puzzle generation.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] A common use of WordNet is to determine the similarity between words.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Various algorithms have been proposed, including measuring the distance among words and synsets in WordNet's graph structure, such as by counting the number of edges among synsets.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The intuition is that the closer two words or synsets are, the closer their meaning.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] A number of WordNet-based word similarity algorithms are implemented in a Perl package called WordNet::Similarity, and in a Python package called NLTK.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Other more sophisticated WordNet-based similarity techniques include ADW, whose implementation is available in Java.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet can also be used to inter-link other vocabularies.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Princeton maintains a list of related projects that includes links to some of the widely used application programming interfaces available for accessing WordNet using various programming languages and environments.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet is connected to several databases of the Semantic Web.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] WordNet is also commonly reused via mappings between the WordNet synsets and the categories from ontologies.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Most often, only the top-level categories of WordNet are mapped.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The Global WordNet Association (GWA) is a public and non-commercial organization that provides a platform for discussing, sharing and connecting wordnets for all languages in the world.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The GWA also promotes the standardization of wordnets across languages, to ensure its uniformity in enumerating the synsets in human languages.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] The GWA keeps a list of wordnets developed around the world.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Projects such as BalkaNet and EuroWordNet made it feasible to create standalone wordnets linked to the original one.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Two such projects were the Russian WordNet, patronized by Petersburg State University of Means of Communication and led by S.A.
[src:word-sense-disambiguation/wordnet] Yablonsky, and Russnet, by Saint Petersburg State University.
